  <section xml:id="sec-prep-sci-not-text">
    <title>Prep Text: Scientific Notation</title>

    <p>To wield scientific notation properly, follow these arcane guidelines:</p>

    <ol>
      <li>
        <p><em>Find the coefficient.</em> Move the decimal point so the number becomes at least 1 but less than 10.
        This becomes the <em>coefficient</em>. For example, <m>32{,}700</m> becomes <m>3.27</m>.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><em>Count the decimal steps.</em> Count how many places you moved the decimal. That number becomes the exponent on your power of ten.
        If you moved the decimal to the left, the exponent is <em>positive</em>. If you moved it to the right, the exponent is <em>negative</em>.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><em>Check your form.</em> The final expression should look like <m>a \times 10^n</m>, where <m>1 \leq |a| &lt; 10</m> and <m>n</m> is an integer.</p>
      </li>
    </ol>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>Convert <m>32,700</m> to scientific notation.</p>
      </statement>
      <hint>
        <p>The decimal point would need to move to the left by 4 places.</p>
      </hint>
      <answer>
        <p><m>3.27 \times 10^4</m></p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>Move the decimal 4 places to the left: <m>32,700 = 3.27 \times 10^4</m>.</p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>Convert <m>0.000089</m> to scientific notation.</p>
      </statement>
      <hint>
        <p>The decimal point would need to move to the right by 5 places.</p>
      </hint>
      <answer>
        <p><m>8.9 \times 10^{-5}</m></p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>Move the decimal 5 places to the right: <m>0.000089 = 8.9 \times 10^{-5}</m>.</p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>

    <p><term>Why Use It?</term></p>
    <p>
      Imagine trying to write the mass of the Earth (~<m>5.97 \times 10^{24}</m> kg) or the mass of an electron
      (~<m>9.1 \times 10^{-31}</m> kg) without magical shorthand!
      Scientific notation saves parchment, keeps calculations neat, and makes comparison of large and small values easier.
    </p>

    <p><term>Bonus Trick: Comparing Powers</term></p>
    <p>
      Scientific notation reveals <em>orders of magnitude</em>.
      Two numbers differ by one order of magnitude for every tenfold difference.
      A dragon's hoard of <m>1 \times 10^6</m> gold coins is
      <em>three orders of magnitude</em> larger than a goblin's pouch of <m>1 \times 10^3</m>.
    </p>

    <p><term>A Final Word from the Grand Mathemagician</term></p>
    <p>
      With scientific notation in your spellbook, you can navigate the vast realms of physics, chemistry, and cosmic measurement.
      Write your numbers with care, check your powers of ten, and let no zero go unwielded.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-prep-sci-not-questions">
    <title>Prep Questions: Scientific Notation</title>
    <!-- Prep q01 -->
    <p><term> Convert standard notation to scientific notation. </term></p>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>Convert <m>0.0072</m> to scientific notation.</p>
      </statement>
      <choices randomize="yes">
        <choice correct="no">
          <statement><p><m>72 \times 10^{-4}</m></p></statement>
          <feedback><p>While this is true, <m>72</m> is greater than <m>10</m>. So this is not considered scientific notation.</p></feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="no">
          <statement><p><m>7.2 \times 10^{3}</m></p></statement>
          <feedback><p>While the decimal moved three, it was moved to the right which results in a negative power of 10.</p></feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement><p><m>7.2 \times 10^{-3}</m></p></statement>
          <feedback><p>Correct! <m>0.0072 = 7.2 \times 10^{-3}</m></p></feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="no">
          <statement><p><m>7.2 \times 10^{-2}</m></p></statement>
          <feedback><p>Your digital blade missed the mark, try again. That's <m>0.072</m>, not <m>0.0072</m>.</p></feedback>
        </choice>
      </choices>
    </exercise>
    <!-- Prep q02 -->
    <exercise>
